g.aria-label: DataLad is a data management and publication multitool based on Git and Git-annex with a command line interface and a Python API. With DataLad, you can version control arbitrarily large data, share or consume data, record your data's provenance, and work computationally reproducible.

g.aria-label: DataLad datasets can contain other DataLad datasets, enabling arbitrarily deep nesting inside of a dataset. Each individual dataset is a modular component with a stand-alone history. A superdataset only registers the version (via commit hash) of the subdataset. A dataset knows its installed subdatasets, but has no way of knowing about its superdataset(s). To apply commands not only to the dataset the action is performed in but also in subdatasets, run commands recursively, i.e. with -r/--recursive.

g.aria-label: Within a dataset the following files contain configurations for DataLad, Git-annex, and Git: .git/config, .datalad/config, .gitmodules, .gitattributes. All but .git/config are version controlled and can be distributed with a dataset. The git config command can modify all but .gitattributes. .gitattributes contains rules about which files to annex based on file path, type and/or size. Environment variables for configurations override options set in configuration files.

g.aria-label: DataLad extensions are additional Python packages that provide (domain-specific) functionality and new commands. The installation is done with standard Python package managers, such as pip, and beyond installation of the package, no additional setup is required. To install a DataLad extension, use $ pip install <extension-name>.
